tResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe mandibular branch of the trigeminal nerve (V3) provides motor innervation to the muscles of mastication, which include the \u003Cstrong\u003Emasseter\u003C/strong\u003E, temporalis, medial pterygoid, and lateral pterygoid. These muscles are responsible for movements of the jaw, such as chewing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ebuccinator\u003C/strong\u003E muscle is innervated by the facial nerve (cranial nerve VII), not the trigeminal nerve. It is involved in actions such as blowing and sucking.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eorbicularis oris\u003C/strong\u003E is also innervated by the facial nerve and is responsible for movements of the lips.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eplatysma\u003C/strong\u003E is a superficial muscle of the neck, also innervated by the facial nerve, and is involved in facial expressions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esternocleidomastoid\u003C/strong\u003E is innervated by the accessory nerve (cranial nerve XI) and is involved in head rotation and flexion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The mandibular branch of the trigeminal nerve (V3) provides motor innervation to the muscles of mastication.","The muscles of mastication include the masseter, temporalis, medial pterygoid, and lateral pterygoid.","The buccinator muscle is innervated by the facial nerve, not the trigeminal nerve."],"references":["Singh, V. (2023). Textbook of Anatomy-Head, Neck and Brain, Volume III-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Patestas, M. A., \u0026 Gartner, L. P. (2016). A textbook of neuroanatomy. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Patel, C. R., Fernandez-Miranda, J. C., Wang, W. H., \u0026 Wang, E. W. (2016). Skull Base Anatomy. Otolaryngologic clinics of North America, 49(1), 9\u201320. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.otc.2015.09.001","Anderson, B. W., Kortz, M. W., Black, A. C., \u0026 Al Kharazi, K. A. (2023). Anatomy, Hea